article.headline: Sting wins sixth straight at home
article.linkText: McKiver provides the fix: Sting sets Sun
article.story:
CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) -- Rookie Teana McKiver is proving to be a
valuable free-agent pickup for the Charlotte Sting.

McKiver scored 12 of her 14 points in the first half and had a
career-high nine rebounds Saturday as the Sting beat the
Connecticut Sun 69-55.

"I'm just trying to fill my role here," said McKiver, a
6-foot-3 backup center out of Tulane.

Andrea Stinson scored 15 points for the Sting (8-5), who won for
the sixth straight time at home.

McKiver, quiet and shy off the court, has found her niche with
tough play and a mean streak. Just ask Connecticut's Taj
McWilliams-Franklin, who took an elbow to the chest from McKiver
that sent her to the locker room for treatment.

"I'm getting more comfortable with the style of play and the
level of play in this league," said McKiver, who had a career-high
15 points earlier this season against Detroit. "And I was lot more
comfortable tonight than I have ever been."

McKiver wasn't drafted, but coach Trudi Lacey saw enough to
invite her to Charlotte for a tryout.

"She had tremendous build and I thought the things she needed
to improve on -- her hands, her defense and her finishing around the
basket -- she's done that," Lacey said. "Again, I think she has
tremendous upside She's a hard worker and she is eager to learn.
You can see her continuous improvement."

Shannon Johnson led Connecticut (6-7) with 17 points and seven
rebounds, while Nykesha Sales added 10 points.

After missing on all eight 3-point attempts in the first half,
the Sting rebounded in the second half. Stinson, Shalonda Enis and
Allison Feaster combined to hit four 3s in the first eight minutes
to open a 15-point lead.

The Sting took a 31-28 halftime lead despite shooting 31
percent. But they made 13 of 14 free throws, and McKiver had a
terrific half.

McKiver scored 12 points and had six offensive rebounds before
the break despite playing only eight minutes. McKiver came into the
game averaging 3.2 points.
